description:
The `final` keyword can:

- stop a **virtual method** from being overridden again
- stop a **class** from being inherited at all

```cpp
class Base {
public:
    virtual void run();
};

class Mid : public Base {
public:
    void run() final; // no more overrides in derived classes
};

class Leaf final : public Mid {
    // cannot derive from Leaf
};
```

This is useful when your design says: "This method should not be changed" or "No one should inherit from this class".

---

## Your task

CBit OS wants a `CoreLogger` that cannot be overridden further.

- Make a base class `BaseLogger` with a **public virtual** method `void log(const std::string& msg)` that prints `"[base] " << msg << "\\n"`.
- Make a class `CoreLogger` that **inherits publicly** from `BaseLogger`.
- In `CoreLogger`, override `log` so it prints `"[core] " << msg << "\\n"`.
- Mark the `CoreLogger::log` method as `final` so no further derived class can override it.

`main` will call `log` through a `BaseLogger*` pointer and also try to derive another logger in comments.

starterCode:
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

// define BaseLogger and CoreLogger here

int main() {
    CoreLogger core;
    BaseLogger* logger = &core;

    logger->log("Starting");

    // If someone tried this, it should not compile:
    // class BadLogger : public CoreLogger {
    // public:
    //     void log(const std::string& msg) override { }
    // };

    return 0;
}
